# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] An **academician** is a full member of an artistic, literary, engineering, or scientific academy.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In many countries, it is an honorific title used to denote a full member of an academy that has a strong influence on national scientific life.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Accordingly, within systems such as the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, the title grants privileges and administrative responsibilities for funding allocation and research priorities.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Being an academician in China is a top honour and title granted only to the nation's top scientists and engineers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Academicians are elected through either the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Chinese Academy of Engineering.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] The British honours "Fellow of the Royal Society" (FRS) or Fellow of the Academy of Social Sciences can be considered rough equivalents.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Fellowship of the Academy of Social Sciences was known as the Award of Academician until July 2014.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering in the UK are recognized as academicians and members include Nobel Prize winners and the nation's top engineers and scientists.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Recently, Nobel Prize winner Frances Arnold was elected to the Royal Academy of Engineering.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In the United States of America, academicians are elected members of the National Academy of Sciences and National Academy of Engineering.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Members include many Nobel Prize, Turing Awards, and Fields Medalists.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Sweden does not use the Academician concept, but membership in learned societies are noted in the Swedish State Calendar.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] The Swedish Royal Academies are independent organizations, founded on Royal command, that act to promote the arts, culture, and science in Sweden.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] The Swedish Academy and Academy of Sciences who are responsible for the selection of Nobel Prize laureates in Literature, Physics, Chemistry, and the Prize in Economic Sciences.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Also included in the Royal Academies are scientific societies that were granted Royal Charters.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] There are a few esteemed Swedish learned societies that has not sought Royal command, including the Society of Sciences in Lund.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Academician may also be a functional title and denote a full member of the National Academy of Sciences in those countries where the academy has a strong influence on national scientific life, particularly countries that were part of, or influenced by, the Soviet Union.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In such countries, academician is used as an honorific title (like "Doctor", "Professor", etc.) when addressing or speaking about someone.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] However, since the reforms of late USSR dismantled the de facto monopoly of the state on forming academies, the creation of voluntary academies has been allowed.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Therefore, it became customary and almost compulsory to list which academy gave the title to assert its meaningfulness.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In Europe, academicians are elected by Pan-European academies, such as the European Academy of Sciences and Arts and the Academia Europaea.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In Canada, fellowship of the Royal Society of Canada is a comparable honour.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In Finland, "Academician" (Finnish: *akateemikko*, Swedish: *akademiker*) is an honorary title and the President of the Republic nominates the Academicians.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] There can be 12 Finnish Academicians representing science and scholarly pursuits and eight Academicians representing fine arts and literature at the same time.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] The Academy of Finland is the state funding agency of Finnish science and letters, but it has no organizational connection to Finnish Academicians.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] The scientists and scholars funded by the Academy of Finland are called Academy Professors (Finnish: *akatemiaprofessori*, Swedish: *akademiprofessor*) and Academy Research Fellows (Finnish: *akatemiatutkija*, Swedish: *akademiforskare*).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In addition to Academy of Finland, Finland has four independent national academies.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Finnish academies are less recognized globally due to its lack of international exposure and use of English language.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] In Taiwan, elected members of *Academia Sinica* are considered academicians.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] A related option of membership also exists in some countries—a *Corresponding Member* is a person who is eminent in respect of scientific results but cannot or does not wish to become a full academy member.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] One of the reasons for this may be that they live far from the academy and it is inconvenient to often travel to its headquarters.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] It is, for example, the case when the person is not a resident in the country which the academy belongs to.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] For communication, such a scientist uses "correspondence".
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Another possible reason is that the charter or traditions of the academy do not admit election of a person to a full membership, unless they have been a corresponding member for a certain period and has demonstrated additional achievements within this period.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/academician] Because of this, in the Russian Academy of Sciences a corresponding membership is a seen as a lower level of membership as compared to the academicians.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He had two brothers Vasily (1904) and Andrei (1911) and a sister Tatyana (1908) (two born sisters died in infancy).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] His father (Nikolai Vasilyevich Nesmeyanov), graduated with excellence Vladimir Gymnasium, and then the Faculty of Law of Moscow University.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He became interested in enlightenment and was working as a public teacher in the village of Bushov (Tula province) for 10 years.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He had married in 1898 and worked at the Moscow city government, then he was a director Bakhrushinsky orphanage in Moscow (1901 – 1917).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Alexander's mother, Lyudmila Danilovna (1878 – 1958), was a multi-talented teacher.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] At ten years Alexander became a vegetarian, and in 1913 he stopped eating fish.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] It was not easy to follow this conviction, especially in the famine years of 1918 – 1921, when roach and herring were an essential food product.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He had become interested in various branches of biology: entomology, hydrobiology, ornithology and from the age of thirteen became interested in chemistry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Strakhov's private Moscow gymnasium, which he graduated with honors.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1917, he entered the natural department of the Faculty of Physics and Mathematics at Moscow University.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] There were no entrance exams due to the passage of the revolution.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Studying in this difficult time required great self-sacrifice and fanatical dedication.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] They studied in unheated rooms and there was not enough laboratory equipment.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Transport was bad, and sometimes Alexander had to walk on foot to the university from Sokolniki.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1920, classes at Moscow State University were frozen due to problems with heating, and Nesmeyanov entered the Military Pedagogical Academy on Bolshaya Gruzinskaya Street.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] At the same time, he worked in the laboratories of the Shanyavsky Moscow City People's University.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] By the end of 1920, Alexander Nikolayevich returned to studies at the academy and at Moscow University, where heating had already been restored.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He meets the "future scientific mentor", Professor N.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] While he was working as a night watchman at the faculty, Nesmeyanov lived in the laboratory of N.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Zelinsky and devoting all his time to scientific experiments.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] After graduating from the university (1922), Nesmeyanov remained at the department of Academician N.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He held the positions of assistant (1924–1938), associate professor, professor (since 1935).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He headed the Department of Organic Chemistry at the Institute of Fine Chemical Technology since 1938.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] From 1939 to 1954 Nesmeyanov was director of the Institute of Organic Chemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1939 he was elected as a corresponding member of Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union, and in 1943 - an academician of Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1946 - 1951 he was an Academician-Secretary of the Department of Chemical Sciences of Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] At the end of the Great Patriotic War, Alexander Nikolayevich returned to his native university.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He headed the Department of Organic Chemistry (1944 – 1958), he was the dean of the Faculty of Chemistry (1944 – 1948), and then became the rector of Moscow State University(1948 – 1951).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thanks to Nesmeyanov's research in the field of organometallic compounds during the war and post-war years, a number of important results were obtained that are of great theoretical and practical importance.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] These studies were aimed at developing methods for the synthesis and studying the chemical properties of various representatives of an important and extensive class of compounds located at the junction of inorganic and organic chemistry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] During the period of Nesmeyanov's rectorship, the construction of a large complex of university buildings on the Sparrow (Lenin) Hills began.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Under his leadership, competent commissions were created to develop technical specifications for the placement of university units in a new location.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] They worked in close creative contact with the author's group of architects (full members of the Academy of Architecture of the USSR L.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Simultaneously with the colossal construction, the development of the university structure is taking place, and curricula are being improved.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thus, courses on the history of sciences were introduced into the curricula of the natural faculties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1948, the Faculty of Biology was reorganized into the Faculty of Biology and Soil.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1949 construction began on an agrobiological station in Chashnikovo.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] At the same time, the Faculty of Geology was created and the departments were organized: crystallography and crystal chemistry; history of geological sciences.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1950, assistance was provided to the University of Chisinau with literature and equipment.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1951, after the death of the President of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, S.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Vavilov Nesmeyanov was summoned to a member of the Politburo of the Central Committee, G.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] On February 16, 1951, at an extraordinary session of the general meeting of the Academy of Sciences, Nesmeyanov was elected its president.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1952, he founded the Institute for Scientific Information.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1954, he opened the Institute of Organoelement Compounds of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, which he led until his death (at present, the institute bears the name of A.N.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] On May 19, 1961, Nesmeyanov resigned as president of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union of his own free will.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In May 1969, at a meeting of the Academic Council of the Institute of Organoelement Compounds, Nesmeyanov spoke out against being elected a senior researcher Candidate of Chemical Sciences Rokhlin, stating “I am a vindictive person.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Last year, Rokhlin was among those who, at an institute rally, spoke out against the introduction of Soviet troops into Czechoslovakia.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] This speech did not affect the results of the vote, and Rokhlin was elected a senior researcher.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Deputy of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR 3-5 convocations (1950 – 1962).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was one of the academicians of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR, who in 1973 signed a letter from scientists to the Pravda newspaper condemning "the behavior of Academician A.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In the letter, Sakharov was accused of having "made a number of statements discrediting the state system, the foreign and domestic policy of the Soviet Union", and academicians assessed his human rights activities as "defaming the honor and dignity of the Soviet scientist".
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was interested in literature and painting, wrote poetry, sketches, was an avid mushroom picker.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was buried in Moscow at the Novodevichy Cemetery.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The first wife – Nina Vladimirovna Koperina (1900–1986) – is a chemist, she has worked at Moscow State University.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Children from the first marriage: Olga (1930–2014) – candidate of chemical sciences; Nikolai (1932–1992) – Doctor of Chemical Sciences, Professor я.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The second wife – Vinogradova Marina Anatolyevna (1921–2013) – is a philologist and a writer.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Nesmeyanov had two brothers and a sister: Andrey Nesmeyanov (1911–1983) – radiochemist, head of the radiochemistry department of Moscow State University, professor, corresponding member of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Vasily Nesmeyanov (1904–1941) – worked as deputy head of the Topographic and Geodetic Service of the Main Directorate of Geodesy and Cartography under the Council of People's Commissars of the USSR.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was shot on July 28, 1941 on charges of espionage.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was rehabilitated on September 17, 1955 by the decision of the Military Collegium of the Supreme Court of the USSR.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Alexander Nikolayevich was one of the greatest organic chemists of the 20th century.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He organised a number of fundamental works on the theory of the structure and reactivity of organic compounds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He created a new discipline lying on the border of inorganic and organic chemistry, which was called "chemistry of organoelement compounds".
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Also he has researched the production of synthetic food, the creation of new drugs and the synthesis of a number of technical materials.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Studying the decomposition of double salts of aryldiazonium halides with mercury halides by copper powder, in 1929 Nesmeyanov proposed a new method for obtaining arylmercury halides.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Later, the diazo method was extended to the synthesis of organometallic compounds of thallium, germanium, tin, lead, arsenic, antimony, and bismuth.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The features of the diazo method, which distinguish it from direct metalation methods, are the possibility of obtaining organometallic compounds with different functional groups in the carbon radical and the possibility of selectively introducing a metal atom into a certain position.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1935 – 1948, Nesmeyanov, together with K.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Kocheshkov, obtained organic derivatives of tin, lead, antimony and other metals.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Due to mutual transitions from organic derivatives of some elements to organic compounds of other elements, organometallic compounds obtained by the diazo method have found new applications in synthesis.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The study by Nesmeyanov of the products of the addition of mercuric chloride to ethylene, acetylene and their derivatives led to the concept of the “dual reactivity” of a substance and the “transfer of the reaction center” along the chain π, π-, σ, π-, σ, σ- and p,π-conjugations in a molecule.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Further research showed that these phenomena are fundamentally different from tautomerism.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] With the participation of his colleague A.E.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Borisov, Nesmeyanov formulated the rule according to which electrophilic and homolytic substitution at the olefin carbon atom occurs with the preservation of the geometric configuration (Nesmeyanov – Borisov rule).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thanks to his research, which showed the enolate structure of ketone derivatives with alkali metals and magnesium, that is, the existence of O-derivatives of ketones, Nesmeyanov refuted Knorr 's concept of "pseudomerism ".
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In the study of the structure of mercury b-, lead- and organotin derivatives of nitrosophenols, Nesmeyanov discovered the phenomenon of metallotropy, that is, a special tautomerism in which a reversible transfer of an organometallic group occurs.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Lutsenko discovered heteroatomic tautomerism (between carbon and oxygen atoms) in keto-enol systems of tin, o- and germanium compounds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Ustynyuk, discovered a new type of metallotropy: it was found that in fluorenylchromium tricarbonyl anions, η 6 -complexes are equilibrium and reversibly isomerized into η 5 -complexes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1954, research into the chemistry of ferrocene began at the Department of Organic Chemistry at Moscow State University and at INEOS under the direction of Nesmeyanov.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] It turned out that the functional derivatives of ferrocene react similarly to aromatic compounds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] However, it has been shown that the electronic effects of the substituents are transmitted through the metallocene core by an inductive mechanism, and therefore have a lesser effect than on benzene derivatives.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Research on ferrocene and its derivatives made it possible to create a number of photosensitive compositions that allow obtaining a stable image on paper, fabric, plastics and metals, and also led to the creation of a new drug, ferrocerone, which fights diseases associated with iron deficiency.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] On the basis of cymantrene, Nesmeyanov proposed a new antiknock agent for motor gasoline.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Rybinskaya, developed a method for the synthesis of various five- and six-membered heterocycles, which is based on the high activity of carbonyl groups and the mobility of the β-substituent in compounds of the type RCOCH=CHX.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The same group of scientists developed the method of "β-ketovinylation", which consists in introducing an RCOCH=CH group into the molecule.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The reaction of β-substituted vinyl ketones with an azide ion made it possible to study the stereochemistry and propose a mechanism for nucleophilic substitution at the activated double bond.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In collaboration with other scientists, Nesmeyanov carried out a number of works in the field of radical telomerization and rearrangement radicals.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In addition to studies of already known reactions, thermal telomerization of ethylene and propylene with silicon hydrides has been developed and other new telomerization reactions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Also, new routes for the synthesis of compounds containing groups such as CCl3, CCl3CHCl, CCl3C<, CCl 2=CH, CCl2=CHX and others.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The study of compounds containing the CCl3-C=C< group showed the rearrangement during reactions with attack on the terminal atoms of the system, which confirmed the presence of σ,π-conjugation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Kost discovered the chain radical isomerization of CCl3CBr=CH2 to CCl2=CClCH2Br under ultraviolet illumination.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In continuation of the work related to the previously created diazo method, Nesmeyanov and L.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Makarova investigated the mechanism of decomposition of aryldiazonium and diaryliodonium salts.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] This made it possible to synthesize new types of onium compounds - diphenylbromonium, diphenylchloronium and triphenyloxonium salts.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Tolstaya and other scientists, Nesmeyanov showed that double salts of diphenylbromonium and diphenylchloronium halides with heavy metal halides are decomposed by powders of the corresponding metals with the formation of organometallic compounds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Thus, the diazo method began to be used to obtain σ-aryl complexes of transition metals and other organometallic compounds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] In 1961, Nesmeyanov formulated the idea of obtaining food by synthetic methods, bypassing agriculture.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Berthelot, as well as an awareness of the modern possibilities of organic synthesis, the problems of preserving the environment and the efficiency of food production.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] The main areas of work were: the development of highly efficient methods for obtaining nutrients; reproduction of the appearance, taste, smell, color, shape, consistency and other properties of natural products in synthetic food substances.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] As a result of research at INEOS, processes have been developed for obtaining black caviar, new forms of potato products, pasta and cereals and combined meat products based on vegetable and animal proteins.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] Alexander Nikolayevich's work on the chemistry of organoelement compounds brought him fame and recognition not only in the Soviet Union, but also in the world.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alexander-nesmeyanov] He was elected an honorary member of several dozen foreign national academies and scientific societies.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/aliphatic-compound] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids are produced by a large variety of organisms including bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] They can be purified from crude extracts of these organisms by acid-base extraction, or solvent extractions followed by silica-gel column chromatography.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Many have found use in traditional or modern medicine, or as starting points for drug discovery.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Other alkaloids possess psychotropic (e.g. psilocin) and stimulant activities (e.g. cocaine, caffeine, nicotine, theobromine), and have been used in entheogenic rituals or as recreational drugs.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids can be toxic (e.g. atropine, tubocurarine).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Although alkaloids act on a diversity of metabolic systems in humans and other animals, they almost uniformly evoke a bitter taste.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The boundary between alkaloids and other nitrogen-containing natural compounds is not clear-cut.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are basic, although some have neutral and even weakly acidic properties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] In addition to carbon, hydrogen and nitrogen, alkaloids may also contain oxygen or sulfur.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Rarer still, they may contain elements such as phosphorus, chlorine, and bromine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Compounds like amino acid peptides, proteins, nucleotides, nucleic acid, amines, and antibiotics are usually not called alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Natural compounds containing nitrogen in the exocyclic position (mescaline, serotonin, dopamine, etc.) are usually classified as amines rather than as alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Some authors, however, consider alkaloids a special case of amines.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The name "alkaloids" (German: *Alkaloide*) was introduced in 1819 by German chemist Carl Friedrich Wilhelm Meissner, and is derived from late Latin root *alkali* and the Greek-language suffix -οειδής -('like').
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] However, the term came into wide use only after the publication of a review article, by Oscar Jacobsen in the chemical dictionary of Albert Ladenburg in the 1880s.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The name "alkaloid" was introduced, since at the time, chemists conceptualized the category of "alkaline" in such a way that plants cannot produce alkaline.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] For instance, potash, an alkaline substance that can be extracted from plants by burning, was thought to be either produced during burning, or extracted by plant from the soil.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Subsequent research by chemists to extract the "principle" (what we nowadays call the active ingredient) of medicinal plants, led to the discovery of various substances that had properties resembling alkalines as understood at the time.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] These substances were variously named "salifiable vegetable bases", "vegetable organic compounds", "organic bases", etc.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] After enough such substances were discovered, these substances were classified as "alkaloid", a new chemical category.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] There is no unique method for naming alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Many individual names are formed by adding the suffix "ine" to the species or genus name.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] For example, atropine is isolated from the plant *Atropa belladonna*; strychnine is obtained from the seed of the Strychnine tree (*Strychnos nux-vomica* L.).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Where several alkaloids are extracted from one plant their names are often distinguished by variations in the suffix: "idine", "anine", "aline", "inine" etc.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] There are also at least 86 alkaloids whose names contain the root "vin" because they are extracted from *vinca* plants such as *Vinca rosea* (*Catharanthus roseus*); these are called *vinca* alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloid-containing plants have been used by humans since ancient times for therapeutic and recreational purposes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] For example, medicinal plants have been known in Mesopotamia from about 2000 BC.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The *Odyssey* of Homer referred to a gift given to Helen by the Egyptian queen, a drug bringing oblivion.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] It is believed that the gift was an opium-containing drug.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] A Chinese book on houseplants written in 1st–3rd centuries BC mentioned a medical use of ephedra and opium poppies.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Also, coca leaves have been used by Indigenous South Americans since ancient times.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Extracts from plants containing toxic alkaloids, such as aconitine and tubocurarine, were used since antiquity for poisoning arrows.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Studies of alkaloids began in the 19th century.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] In 1804, the German chemist Friedrich Sertürner isolated from opium a "soporific principle" (Latin: *principium somniferum*), which he called "morphium", referring to Morpheus, the Greek god of dreams; in German and some other Central-European languages, this is still the name of the drug.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The term "morphine", used in English and French, was given by the French physicist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] A significant contribution to the chemistry of alkaloids in the early years of its development was made by the French researchers Pierre Joseph Pelletier and Joseph Bienaimé Caventou, who discovered quinine (1820) and strychnine (1818).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Several other alkaloids were discovered around that time, including xanthine (1817), atropine (1819), caffeine (1820), coniine (1827), nicotine (1828), colchicine (1833), sparteine (1851), and cocaine (1860).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The development of the chemistry of alkaloids was accelerated by the emergence of spectroscopic and chromatographic methods in the 20th century, so that by 2008 more than 12,000 alkaloids had been identified.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The first complete synthesis of an alkaloid was achieved in 1886 by the German chemist Albert Ladenburg.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] He produced coniine by reacting 2-methylpyridine with acetaldehyde and reducing the resulting 2-propenyl pyridine with sodium.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Compared with most other classes of natural compounds, alkaloids are characterized by a great structural diversity.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Initially, when knowledge of chemical structures was lacking, botanical classification of the source plants was relied on.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] This classification is now considered obsolete.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] More recent classifications are based on similarity of the carbon skeleton (*e.g.*, indole-, isoquinoline-, and pyridine-like) or biochemical precursor (ornithine, lysine, tyrosine, tryptophan, etc.).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] However, they require compromises in borderline cases; for example, nicotine contains a pyridine fragment from nicotinamide and a pyrrolidine part from ornithine and therefore can be assigned to both classes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] "Protoalkaloids", which contain nitrogen (but not the nitrogen heterocycle) and also originate from amino acids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Examples include mescaline, adrenaline and ephedrine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Polyamine alkaloids – derivatives of putrescine, spermidine, and spermine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Pseudoalkaloids – alkaloid-like compounds that do not originate from amino acids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] This group includes terpene-like and steroid-like alkaloids, as well as purine-like alkaloids such as caffeine, theobromine, theacrine and theophylline.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Some authors classify ephedrine and cathinone as pseudoalkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Those originate from the amino acid phenylalanine, but acquire their nitrogen atom not from the amino acid but through transamination.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Some alkaloids do not have the carbon skeleton characteristic of their group.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] So, galanthamine and homoaporphines do not contain isoquinoline fragment, but are, in general, attributed to isoquinoline alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most alkaloids contain oxygen in their molecular structure; those compounds are usually colorless crystals at ambient conditions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Oxygen-free alkaloids, such as nicotine or coniine, are typically volatile, colorless, oily liquids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Some alkaloids are colored, like berberine (yellow) and sanguinarine (orange).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are weak bases, but some, such as theobromine and theophylline, are amphoteric.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Many alkaloids dissolve poorly in water but readily dissolve in organic solvents, such as diethyl ether, chloroform or 1,2-dichloroethane.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Caffeine, cocaine, codeine and nicotine are slightly soluble in water (with a solubility of ≥1g/L), whereas others, including morphine and yohimbine are very slightly water-soluble (0.1–1 g/L).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids and acids form salts of various strengths.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] These salts are usually freely soluble in water and ethanol and poorly soluble in most organic solvents.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Exceptions include scopolamine hydrobromide, which is soluble in organic solvents, and the water-soluble quinine sulfate.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most alkaloids have a bitter taste or are poisonous when ingested.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloid production in plants appeared to have evolved in response to feeding by herbivorous animals; however, some animals have evolved the ability to detoxify alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Some alkaloids can produce developmental defects in the offspring of animals that consume but cannot detoxify the alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] One example is the alkaloid cyclopamine, produced in the leaves of corn lily.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] During the 1950s, up to 25% of lambs born by sheep that had grazed on corn lily had serious facial deformations.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] These ranged from deformed jaws to cyclopia.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] After decades of research, in the 1980s, the compound responsible for these deformities was identified as the alkaloid 11-deoxyjervine, later renamed to cyclopamine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids are generated by various living organisms, especially by higher plants – about 10 to 25% of those contain alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Therefore, in the past the term "alkaloid" was associated with plants.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The alkaloids content in plants is usually within a few percent and is inhomogeneous over the plant tissues.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Depending on the type of plants, the maximum concentration is observed in the leaves (for example, black henbane), fruits or seeds (Strychnine tree), root (*Rauvolfia serpentina*) or bark (cinchona).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Furthermore, different tissues of the same plants may contain different alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Beside plants, alkaloids are found in certain types of fungus, such as psilocybin in the fruiting bodies of the genus *Psilocybe*, and in animals, such as bufotenin in the skin of some toads and a number of insects, markedly ants.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Many marine organisms also contain alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Some amines, such as adrenaline and serotonin, which play an important role in higher animals, are similar to alkaloids in their structure and biosynthesis and are sometimes called alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Because of the structural diversity of alkaloids, there is no single method of their extraction from natural raw materials.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most methods exploit the property of most alkaloids to be soluble in organic solvents but not in water, and the opposite tendency of their salts.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Their mixture is extracted first and then individual alkaloids are separated.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Plants are thoroughly ground before extraction.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most alkaloids are present in the raw plants in the form of salts of organic acids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The extracted alkaloids may remain salts or change into bases.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Base extraction is achieved by processing the raw material with alkaline solutions and extracting the alkaloid bases with organic solvents, such as 1,2-dichloroethane, chloroform, diethyl ether or benzene.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Then, the impurities are dissolved by weak acids; this converts alkaloid bases into salts that are washed away with water.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] If necessary, an aqueous solution of alkaloid salts is again made alkaline and treated with an organic solvent.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The process is repeated until the desired purity is achieved.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] In the acidic extraction, the raw plant material is processed by a weak acidic solution (*e.g.*, acetic acid in water, ethanol, or methanol).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] A base is then added to convert alkaloids to basic forms that are extracted with organic solvent (if the extraction was performed with alcohol, it is removed first, and the remainder is dissolved in water).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The solution is purified as described above.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids are separated from their mixture using their different solubility in certain solvents and different reactivity with certain reagents or by distillation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] A number of alkaloids are identified from insects, among which the fire ant venom alkaloids known as solenopsins have received greater attention from researchers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] These insect alkaloids can be efficiently extracted by solvent immersion of live fire ants or by centrifugation of live ants followed by silica-gel chromatography purification.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Tracking and dosing the extracted solenopsin ant alkaloids has been described as possible based on their absorbance peak around 232 nanometers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Biological precursors of most alkaloids are amino acids, such as ornithine, lysine, phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan, histidine, aspartic acid, and anthranilic acid.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Nicotinic acid can be synthesized from tryptophan or aspartic acid.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Ways of alkaloid biosynthesis are too numerous and cannot be easily classified.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] However, there are a few typical reactions involved in the biosynthesis of various classes of alkaloids, including synthesis of Schiff bases and Mannich reaction.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Schiff bases can be obtained by reacting amines with ketones or aldehydes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] These reactions are a common method of producing C=N bonds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] An integral component of the Mannich reaction, in addition to an amine and a carbonyl compound, is a carbanion, which plays the role of the nucleophile in the nucleophilic addition to the ion formed by the reaction of the amine and the carbonyl.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] In addition to the described above monomeric alkaloids, there are also dimeric, and even trimeric and tetrameric alkaloids formed upon condensation of two, three, and four monomeric alkaloids.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] There are also dimeric alkaloids formed from two distinct monomers, such as the *vinca* alkaloids vinblastine and vincristine, which are formed from the coupling of catharanthine and vindoline.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] The newer semi-synthetic chemotherapeutic agent vinorelbine is used in the treatment of non-small-cell lung cancer.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] It is another derivative dimer of vindoline and catharanthine and is synthesised from anhydrovinblastine, starting either from leurosine or the monomers themselves.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids are among the most important and best-known secondary metabolites, i.e. biogenic substances not directly involved in the normal growth, development, or reproduction of the organism.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Instead, they generally mediate ecological interactions, which may produce a selective advantage for the organism by increasing its survivability or fecundity.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] In some cases their function, if any, remains unclear.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] An early hypothesis, that alkaloids are the final products of nitrogen metabolism in plants, as urea and uric acid are in mammals, was refuted by the finding that their concentration fluctuates rather than steadily increasing.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Most of the known functions of alkaloids are related to protection.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] For example, aporphine alkaloid liriodenine produced by the tulip tree protects it from parasitic mushrooms.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] In addition, the presence of alkaloids in the plant prevents insects and chordate animals from eating it.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] However, some animals are adapted to alkaloids and even use them in their own metabolism.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Such alkaloid-related substances as serotonin, dopamine and histamine are important neurotransmitters in animals.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Alkaloids are also known to regulate plant growth.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] One example of an organism that uses alkaloids for protection is the *Utetheisa ornatrix*, more commonly known as the ornate moth.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Pyrrolizidine alkaloids render these larvae and adult moths unpalatable to many of their natural enemies like coccinelid beetles, green lacewings, insectivorous hemiptera and insectivorous bats.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Another example of alkaloids being utilized occurs in the poison hemlock moth (*Agonopterix alstroemeriana).* This moth feeds on its highly toxic and alkaloid-rich host plant poison hemlock (*Conium maculatum*) during its larval stage.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] *A. alstroemeriana* may benefit twofold from the toxicity of the naturally occurring alkaloids, both through the unpalatability of the species to predators and through the ability of *A. alstroemeriana* to recognize *Conium maculatum* as the correct location for oviposition.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] A fire ant venom alkaloid known as solenopsin has been demonstrated to protect queens of invasive fire ants during the foundation of new nests, thus playing a central role in the spread of this pest ant species around the world.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Medical use of alkaloid-containing plants has a long history, and, thus, when the first alkaloids were isolated in the 19th century, they immediately found application in clinical practice.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Many synthetic and semisynthetic drugs are structural modifications of the alkaloids, which were designed to enhance or change the primary effect of the drug and reduce unwanted side-effects.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] For example, naloxone, an opioid receptor antagonist, is a derivative of thebaine that is present in opium.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Prior to the development of a wide range of relatively low-toxic synthetic pesticides, some alkaloids, such as salts of nicotine and anabasine, were used as insecticides.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Their use was limited by their high toxicity to humans.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Preparations of plants and fungi containing alkaloids and their extracts, and later pure alkaloids, have long been used as psychoactive substances.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Cocaine, caffeine, and cathinone are stimulants of the central nervous system.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Mescaline and many indole alkaloids (such as psilocybin, dimethyltryptamine and ibogaine) have hallucinogenic effect.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Morphine and codeine are strong narcotic pain killers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] There are alkaloids that do not have strong psychoactive effect themselves, but are precursors for semi-synthetic psychoactive drugs.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] For example, ephedrine and pseudoephedrine are used to produce methcathinone and methamphetamine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/alkaloid] Thebaine is used in the synthesis of many painkillers such as oxycodone.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] An **analgesic drug**, also called simply an **analgesic**, **antalgic**, **pain reliever**, or **painkiller**, is any member of the group of drugs used for pain management.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Analgesics are conceptually distinct from anesthetics, which temporarily reduce, and in some instances eliminate, sensation, although analgesia and anesthesia are neurophysiologically overlapping and thus various drugs have both analgesic and anesthetic effects.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Analgesic choice is also determined by the type of pain: For neuropathic pain, recent research has suggested that classes of drugs that are not normally considered analgesics, such as tricyclic antidepressants and anticonvulsants may be considered as an alternative.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Various analgesics, such as many NSAIDs, are available over the counter in most countries, whereas various others are prescription drugs owing to the substantial risks and high chances of overdose, misuse, and addiction in the absence of medical supervision.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The word *analgesic* derives from Greek *an-* (ἀν-, "without"), *álgos* (ἄλγος, "pain"), and *-ikos* (-ικος, forming adjectives).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Such drugs were usually known as "anodynes" before the 20th century.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Analgesics are typically classified based on their mechanism of action.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Paracetamol, also known as acetaminophen or APAP, is a medication used to treat pain and fever.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] It is typically used for mild to moderate pain.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] In combination with opioid pain medication, paracetamol is now used for more severe pain such as cancer pain and after surgery.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] It is typically used either by mouth or rectally but is also available intravenously.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Effects last between two and four hours.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Paracetamol is classified as a mild analgesic, and is generally safe at recommended doses.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (usually abbreviated to NSAIDs), are a drug class that groups together drugs that decrease pain and lower fever, and, in higher doses, decrease inflammation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The most prominent members of this group of drugs — aspirin, ibuprofen, naproxen, and diclofenac — are all available over the counter in most countries.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] These drugs have been derived from NSAIDs.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The cyclooxygenase enzyme inhibited by NSAIDs was discovered to have at least two different versions: COX1 and COX2.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Research suggested most of the adverse effects of NSAIDs to be mediated by blocking the COX1 (constitutive) enzyme, with the analgesic effects being mediated by the COX2 (inducible) enzyme.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Thus, the COX2 inhibitors were developed to inhibit only the COX2 enzyme (traditional NSAIDs block both versions in general).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] These drugs (such as rofecoxib, celecoxib, and etoricoxib) are equally effective analgesics when compared with NSAIDs, but cause less gastrointestinal hemorrhage in particular.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] After widespread adoption of the COX-2 inhibitors, it was discovered that most of the drugs in this class increase the risk of cardiovascular events by 40% on average.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] This led to the withdrawal of rofecoxib and valdecoxib, and warnings on others.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Etoricoxib seems relatively safe, with the risk of thrombotic events similar to that of non-coxib NSAID diclofenac.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Morphine, the archetypal opioid, and other opioids (e.g., codeine, oxycodone, hydrocodone, dihydromorphine, pethidine) all exert a similar influence on the cerebral opioid receptor system.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Buprenorphine is a partial agonist of the μ-opioid receptor, and tramadol is a serotonin norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (SNRI) with weak μ-opioid receptor agonist properties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Tramadol is structurally closer to venlafaxine than to codeine and delivers analgesia by not only delivering "opioid-like" effects (through mild agonism of the mu receptor) but also by acting as a weak but fast-acting serotonin releasing agent and norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Tapentadol, with some structural similarities to tramadol, presents what is believed to be a novel drug working through two (and possibly three) different modes of action in the fashion of both a traditional opioid and as an SNRI.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The effects of serotonin and norepinephrine on pain, while not completely understood, have had causal links established and drugs in the SNRI class are commonly used in conjunction with opioids (especially tapentadol and tramadol) with greater success in pain relief.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Dosing of all opioids may be limited by opioid toxicity (confusion, respiratory depression, myoclonic jerks and pinpoint pupils), seizures (tramadol), but opioid-tolerant individuals usually have higher dose ceilings than patients without tolerance.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Opioids, while very effective analgesics, may have some unpleasant side-effects.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Patients starting morphine may experience nausea and vomiting (generally relieved by a short course of antiemetics such as phenergan).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Pruritus (itching) may require switching to a different opioid.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Constipation occurs in almost all patients on opioids, and laxatives (lactulose, macrogol-containing or co-danthramer) are typically co-prescribed.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] When used appropriately, opioids and other central analgesics are safe and effective; however, risks such as addiction and the body's becoming used to the drug (tolerance) can occur.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The effect of tolerance means that frequent use of the drug may result in its diminished effect.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] When safe to do so, the dosage may need to be increased to maintain effectiveness against tolerance, which may be of particular concern regarding patients with chronic pain and requiring an analgesic over long periods.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Opioid tolerance is often addressed with opioid rotation therapy in which a patient is routinely switched between two or more non-cross-tolerant opioid medications in order to prevent exceeding safe dosages in the attempt to achieve an adequate analgesic effect.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Opioid tolerance should not be confused with opioid-induced hyperalgesia.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The symptoms of these two conditions can appear very similar but the mechanism of action is different.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Opioid-induced hyperalgesia is when exposure to opioids increases the sensation of pain (hyperalgesia) and can even make non-painful stimuli painful (allodynia).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Alcohol has biological, mental, and social effects which influence the consequences of using alcohol for pain.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Moderate use of alcohol can lessen certain types of pain in certain circumstances.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The majority of its analgesic effects come from antagonizing NMDA receptors, similarly to ketamine, thus decreasing the activity of the primary excitatory (signal boosting) neurotransmitter, glutamate.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] It also functions as an analgesic to a lesser degree by increasing the activity of the primary inhibitory (signal reducing) neurotransmitter, GABA.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Attempting to use alcohol to treat pain has also been observed to lead to negative outcomes including excessive drinking and alcohol use disorder.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Analgesics are frequently used in combination, such as the paracetamol and codeine preparations found in many non-prescription pain relievers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] They can also be found in combination with vasoconstrictor drugs such as pseudoephedrine for sinus-related preparations, or with antihistamine drugs for people with allergies.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Moreover, these combination analgesics can often result in significant adverse events, including accidental overdoses, most often due to confusion that arises from the multiple (and often non-acting) components of these combinations.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] There is some evidence that some treatments using alternative medicine can relieve some types of pain more effectively than placebo.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The available research concludes that more research would be necessary to better understand the use of alternative medicine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Nefopam—a monoamine reuptake inhibitor, and calcium and sodium channel modulator—is also approved for the treatment of moderate to severe pain in some countries.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Flupirtine is a centrally acting K+ channel opener with weak NMDA antagonist properties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] It was used in Europe for moderate to strong pain, as well as its migraine-treating and muscle-relaxant properties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] It has no significant anticholinergic properties, and is believed to be devoid of any activity on dopamine, serotonin, or histamine receptors.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] It is not addictive, and tolerance usually does not develop.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] However, tolerance may develop in some cases.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Ziconotide, a blocker of potent N-type voltage-gated calcium channels, is administered intrathecally for the relief of severe, usually cancer-related pain.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Certain drugs that have been introduced for uses other than analgesics are also used in pain management.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Both first-generation (such as amitriptyline) and newer antidepressants (such as duloxetine) are used alongside NSAIDs and opioids for pain involving nerve damage and similar problems.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Other agents directly potentiate the effects of analgesics, such as using hydroxyzine, promethazine, carisoprodol, or tripelennamine to increase the pain-killing ability of a given dose of opioid analgesic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Adjuvant analgesics, also called atypical analgesics, include orphenadrine, mexiletine, pregabalin, gabapentin, cyclobenzaprine, hyoscine (scopolamine), and other drugs possessing anticonvulsant, anticholinergic, and/or antispasmodic properties, as well as many other drugs with CNS actions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] These drugs are used along with analgesics to modulate and/or modify the action of opioids when used against pain, especially of neuropathic origin.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Dextromethorphan has been noted to slow the development of and reverse tolerance to opioids, as well as to exert additional analgesia by acting upon NMDA receptors, as does ketamine.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Some analgesics such as methadone and ketobemidone and perhaps piritramide have intrinsic NMDA action.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] The anticonvulsant carbamazepine is used to treat neuropathic pain.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Similarly, the gabapentinoids gabapentin and pregabalin are prescribed for neuropathic pain, and phenibut is available without prescription.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Gabapentinoids work as α2δ-subunit blockers of voltage-gated calcium channels, and tend to have other mechanisms of action as well.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Gabapentinoids are all anticonvulsants, which are most commonly used for neuropathic pain, as their mechanism of action tends to inhibit pain sensation originating from the nervous system.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Topical analgesia is generally recommended to avoid systemic side-effects.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Painful joints, for example, may be treated with an ibuprofen- or diclofenac-containing gel (The labeling for topical diclofenac has been updated to warn about drug-induced hepatotoxicity.); capsaicin also is used topically.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Lidocaine, an anesthetic, and steroids may be injected into joints for longer-term pain relief.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Lidocaine is also used for painful mouth sores and to numb areas for dental work and minor medical procedures.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] In February 2007 the FDA notified consumers and healthcare professionals of the potential hazards of topical anesthetics entering the bloodstream when applied in large doses to the skin without medical supervision.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] These topical anesthetics contain anesthetic drugs such as lidocaine, tetracaine, benzocaine, and prilocaine in a cream, ointment, or gel.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Topical nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs provide pain relief in common conditions such as muscle sprains and overuse injuries.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p01] Since the side effects are also lesser, topical preparations could be preferred over oral medications in these conditions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analgesics-p02] Some novel and investigational analgesics include subtype-selective voltage-gated sodium channel blockers such as funapide and raxatrigine, as well as multimodal agents such as ralfinamide.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] It encompasses both classical techniques (e.g. titration, gravimetric analysis) and modern instrumental approaches (e.g. spectroscopy, chromatography, mass spectrometry, electrochemical methods).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] There is also a strong trend towards miniaturization, automation, and the development of real-time, point-of-care diagnostic sensors.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has been important since the early days of chemistry, providing methods for determining which elements and chemicals are present in the object in question.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] During this period, significant contributions to analytical chemistry included the development of systematic elemental analysis by Justus von Liebig and systematized organic analysis based on the specific reactions of functional groups.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The first instrumental analysis was flame emissive spectrometry, developed by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff, who discovered rubidium (Rb) and caesium (Cs) in 1860.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Most of the major developments in analytical chemistry took place after 1900.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] During this period, instrumental analysis became progressively dominant in the field.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In particular, many of the basic spectroscopic and spectrometric techniques were discovered in the early 20th century and refined in the late 20th century.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The separation sciences follow a similar timeline of development and have also became increasingly transformed into high-performance instruments.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In the 1970s many of these techniques began to be used together as hybrid techniques to achieve a complete characterization of samples.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Starting in the 1970s, analytical chemistry became progressively more inclusive of biological questions (bioanalytical chemistry), whereas it had previously been largely focused on inorganic or small organic molecules.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Lasers have been increasingly used as probes and even to initiate and influence a wide variety of reactions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The late 20th century also saw an expansion of the application of analytical chemistry from somewhat academic chemical questions to forensic, environmental, industrial and medical questions, such as in histology.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Modern analytical chemistry is dominated by instrumental analysis.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Many analytical chemists focus on a single type of instrument.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Academics tend to either focus on new applications and discoveries or on new methods of analysis.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The discovery of a chemical present in blood that increases the risk of cancer would be a discovery that an analytical chemist might be involved in.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] An effort to develop a new method might involve the use of a tunable laser to increase the specificity and sensitivity of a spectrometric method.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Many methods, once developed, are kept purposely static so that data can be compared over long periods of time.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] This is particularly true in industrial quality assurance (QA), forensic, and environmental applications.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry plays an increasingly important role in the pharmaceutical industry where, aside from QA, it is used in the discovery of new drug candidates and in clinical applications where understanding the interactions between the drug and the patient are critical.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The 21st century has been defined by the digitalization of analytical chemistry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The handling of large datasets ("big data") from instruments like Orbitrap mass spectrometers has made advanced data analysis, including machine learning, an essential skill.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] This era also focuses strongly on sustainability, leading to the green chemistry subfield of Green Analytical Chemistry, which aims to minimize the environmental impact of chemical analyses.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Although modern analytical chemistry is dominated by sophisticated instrumentation, the roots of analytical chemistry and some of the principles used in modern instruments are from traditional techniques, many of which are still used today.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] These techniques also tend to form the backbone of most undergraduate analytical chemistry educational labs.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] There are numerous qualitative chemical tests; examples include the acid test for gold and the Kastle-Meyer test for the presence of blood.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Inorganic qualitative analysis generally refers to a systematic scheme to confirm the presence of certain aqueous ions or elements by performing a series of reactions that eliminate a range of possibilities and then confirm suspected ions with a confirming test.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Sometimes small carbon-containing ions are included in such schemes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] With modern instrumentation, these tests are rarely used but can be useful for educational purposes and in fieldwork or other situations where access to state-of-the-art instruments is not available or expedient.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Quantitative analysis is the measurement of the quantities of particular chemical constituents present in a substance.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Quantities can be measured by mass (gravimetric analysis) or volume (volumetric analysis).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Gravimetric analysis involves determining the amount of material present by weighing the sample before and/or after some transformation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] A common example used in undergraduate education is the determination of the amount of water in a hydrate by heating the sample to remove the water such that the difference in weight is due to the loss of water.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Titration involves the gradual addition of a measurable reactant to an exact volume of a solution being analyzed until some equivalence point is reached.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Titration is a family of techniques used to determine the concentration of an analyte.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Titrating accurately to either the half-equivalence point or the endpoint of a titration allows the chemist to determine the amount of moles used, which can then be used to determine a concentration or composition of the titrant.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Most familiar to those who have taken chemistry during secondary education is the acid-base titration involving a color-changing pH indicator, such as phenolphthalein.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] There are many other types of titrations, including potentiometric titrations and precipitation titrations.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Chemists might also create titration curves by systematically testing the pH after every added drop in order to understand different properties of the titrant.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Spectroscopy measures the interaction of the molecules with electromagnetic radiation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Mass spectrometry measures mass-to-charge ratio of molecules using electric and magnetic fields.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In a mass spectrometer, a small amount of sample is ionized and converted to gaseous ions, where they are separated and analyzed according to their mass-to-charge ratios.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] There are several ionization methods: electron ionization, chemical ionization, electrospray ionization, fast atom bombardment, matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization, and others.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Also, mass spectrometry is categorized by approaches of mass analyzers: magnetic-sector, quadrupole mass analyzer, quadrupole ion trap, time-of-flight, Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance, and so on.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Electroanalytical methods measure the potential (volts) and/or current (amps) in an electrochemical cell containing the analyte.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] These methods can be categorized according to which aspects of the cell are controlled and which are measured.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Calorimetry and thermogravimetric analysis measure the interaction of a material and heat.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Separation processes are used to decrease the complexity of material mixtures.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Chromatography, electrophoresis and field flow fractionation are representative of this field.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Chromatography can be used to determine the presence of substances in a sample, as different components in a mixture have different tendencies to adsorb onto the stationary phase or dissolve in the mobile phase.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Thus, different components of the mixture move at different speeds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Different components of a mixture can therefore be identified by their respective R*ƒ* values, which is the ratio between the migration distance of the substance and the migration distance of the solvent front during chromatography.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In combination with the instrumental methods, chromatography can be used in the quantitative determination of substances.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] There are different types of chromatography that differ from the media they use to separate the analyte and the sample.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In thin-layer chromatography, the analyte mixture moves up and separates along the coated sheet under the volatile mobile phase.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In gas chromatography, the gas phase separates the volatile analytes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] A common method of chromatography using liquid as a mobile phase is high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Combinations of the above techniques produce a "hybrid" or "hyphenated" technique.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Several examples are in popular use today and new hybrid techniques are under development.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] For example, gas chromatography-mass spectrometry, gas chromatography-infrared spectroscopy, liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry, liquid chromatography-NMR spectroscopy, liquid chromatography-infrared spectroscopy, and capillary electrophoresis-mass spectrometry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Hyphenated separation techniques refer to a combination of two (or more) techniques to detect and separate chemicals from solutions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Most often the other technique is some form of chromatography.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Hyphenated techniques are widely used in chemistry and biochemistry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] A slash is sometimes used instead of hyphen, especially if the name of one of the methods contains a hyphen itself.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The visualization of single molecules, single cells, biological tissues, and nanomaterials is an important and attractive approach in analytical science.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Also, hybridization with other traditional analytical tools is revolutionizing analytical science.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Microscopy can be categorized into three different fields: optical microscopy, electron microscopy, and scanning probe microscopy.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Recently, this field is rapidly progressing because of the rapid development of the computer and camera industries.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Devices that integrate (multiple) laboratory functions on a single chip of only millimeters to a few square centimeters in size and that are capable of handling extremely small fluid volumes down to less than picoliters.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The vast amount of data produced by modern analytical instruments has made computational data analysis an integral part of the field.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The field of chemometrics uses statistical and mathematical methods to design optimal experimental procedures and to extract meaningful information from chemical data.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Error can be defined as numerical difference between observed value and true value.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The experimental error can be divided into two types, systematic error and random error.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Systematic error results from a flaw in equipment or the design of an experiment while random error results from uncontrolled or uncontrollable variables in the experiment.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] An error of a measurement is an inverse measure of accurate measurement (i.e., smaller the error greater the accuracy of the measurement).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] To use these values in a function, it may be useful to calculate the error of the function.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] A general method for analysis of concentration involves the creation of a calibration curve.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] This allows for the determination of the amount of a chemical in a material by comparing the results of an unknown sample to those of a series of known standards.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] If the concentration of an element or compound in a sample exceeds the detection range of the technique, it can simply be diluted in a pure solvent.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] If the amount in the sample is below an instrument's range of measurement, the method of addition can be used.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In this method, a known quantity of the element or compound under study is added, and the difference between the concentration added and the concentration observed is the amount actually in the sample.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Sometimes an internal standard is added at a known concentration directly to an analytical sample to aid in quantitation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The amount of analyte present is then determined relative to the internal standard as a calibrant.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] An ideal internal standard is an isotopically enriched analyte which gives rise to the method of isotope dilution.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The method of standard addition is used in instrumental analysis to determine the concentration of a substance (analyte) in an unknown sample by comparison to a set of samples of known concentration, similar to using a calibration curve.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Standard addition can be applied to most analytical techniques and is used instead of a calibration curve to solve the matrix effect problem.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] One of the most important components of analytical chemistry is maximizing the desired signal while minimizing the associated noise.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The analytical figure of merit is known as the signal-to-noise ratio (S/N or SNR).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Noise can arise from environmental factors as well as from fundamental physical processes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Thermal noise results from the motion of charge carriers (usually electrons) in an electrical circuit generated by their thermal motion.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Thermal noise is white noise, meaning that the power spectral density is constant throughout the frequency spectrum.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] where *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *R* is the resistance, and $\Delta f$ is the bandwidth of the frequency f .
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Shot noise is a type of electronic noise that occurs when the finite number of particles (such as electrons in an electronic circuit or photons in an optical device) is small enough to give rise to statistical fluctuations in a signal.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Shot noise is a Poisson process, and the charge carriers that make up the current follow a Poisson distribution.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] where *e* is the elementary charge and *I* is the average current.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Flicker noise is electronic noise with a 1/*ƒ* frequency spectrum; as *f* increases, the noise decreases.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Flicker noise arises from a variety of sources, such as impurities in a conductive channel, generation, and recombination noise in a transistor due to base current, and so on.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] This noise can be avoided by modulation of the signal at a higher frequency, for example, through the use of a lock-in amplifier.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Environmental noise arises from the surroundings of the analytical instrument.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Sources of electromagnetic noise are power lines, radio and television stations, wireless devices, compact fluorescent lamps and electric motors.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Many of these noise sources are narrow bandwidth and, therefore, can be avoided.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Temperature and vibration isolation may be required for some instruments.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Noise reduction can be accomplished either in computer hardware or software.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Examples of hardware noise reduction are the use of shielded cable, analog filtering, and signal modulation.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Examples of software noise reduction are digital filtering, ensemble average, boxcar average, and correlation methods.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has applications across science and industry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Great effort is being put into shrinking the analysis techniques to chip size.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Although few examples of such systems compete with traditional analysis techniques, potential advantages include size/portability, speed, and cost.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Micro total analysis system (μTAS) or lab-on-a-chip.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Microscale chemistry reduces the amount of chemicals used.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Many developments improve the analysis of biological systems.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has played a critical role in the understanding of basic science to a variety of practical applications, such as biomedical applications, environmental monitoring, quality control of industrial manufacturing, and forensic science.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] The recent developments in computer automation and information technologies have extended analytical chemistry into several new biological fields.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] For example, automated DNA sequencing machines were the basis for completing human genome projects, leading to the birth of genomics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Protein identification and peptide sequencing by mass spectrometry opened a new field of proteomics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] In addition to automating specific processes, there is effort to automate larger sections of lab testing, such as in companies like Emerald Cloud Lab and Transcriptic.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has been an indispensable area in the development of nanotechnology.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/analytical-chemistry] Surface characterization instruments, electron microscopes and scanning probe microscopes enable scientists to visualize atomic structures with chemical characterizations.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Currently, there are more than 4,500 students in nine areas of undergraduate, 28 master's programs and 23 scientific specialties for training of candidates and doctors of science.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In MITHT there are eight dissertation councils for doctoral and PhD theses.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Research and teaching activities are performed by more than 400 professors and 158 scientists, including more than 120 doctors of science and professors.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Located in Moscow at Vernadsky Avenue, Building 86 (new building complex) and Malaya Pirogovskaya, Building 1 (historic building).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] History of the university and its continuing operations as a higher education institution begins 1 July 1900 and covers several stages.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] 1 July (14 July, New Style) 1900 was organized the Moscow Higher Women Courses (MHWC).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Their structure originally consisted of two departments: History and Philosophy and Physics and Mathematics.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] On the last one were soon opened two offices: mathematical and natural, and after a few years two more – medical and chemical-pharmaceutical.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The initiators and the first lecturers were outstanding scientists, academics subsequently S.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Zelinsky (the inventor of the gas mask (1916)), Professors V.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The first director of MHWC was Professor V.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Chaplygin, the leading scientist in the field of hydro- and aerodynamics, the organizer of the construction of school buildings on the Malaya Pirogovskaya street (formerly Devichie Pole).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] By the beginning of World War I MHWC turned into one of the largest higher education institutions in the country.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The number of trainees reached 710, and during the existence of courses released 5760 professionals.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In turning into a first-class university MHWC paramount importance had an exceptional organizational skill of S.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Chaplygin, later shown to them with equal brilliance in creating TsAGI.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] 16 October 1918 MHWC were converted into second Moscow State University.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The first rector of the 2nd Moscow State University was appointed academician S.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Nametkin who worked since 1913 as a head of the Department of Organic Chemistry of MHWC.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] As part of the 2nd Moscow State University became the chemical-pharmaceutical department, which in 1919 was transformed into the chemical and pharmaceutical department.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] At this time, on the faculty worked well-known Professors A.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Faculty graduates go to work in the factories, involve in the implementation of research projects that receive a wide scope.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] During 1922 – 1928 years it has been published about 300 papers and 11 monographs.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The greatest successes are achieved in the fields of organic and pharmaceutical chemistry under the direction of heads of departments, academics S.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Production of new drugs being introduced in the pharmaceutical factory belonging to faculty.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] 18 April 1930 by order of the People's Commissariat second MSU was reorganized into three independent institutions: Medical (now RSMU them.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Pirogov) Pedagogical (now MPSU), and Chemical Technology (now MITHT).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Last transferred to the jurisdiction of the Vsehimprom VSNKh USSR.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In addressing this issue directly involved Sergo Ordzhonikidze.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] 10 May 1931 Chemical and Pharmaceutical Faculty became an independent and received a new name – the Moscow Institute of Fine Chemical Technology (MITHT).
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Historically, the name of the institute is due to the nature of objects that are studied by students: they were small capacity chemical and pharmaceutical technology, technology of platinum group metals and rare-earth elements.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] From this moment begins a new stage of development of the institution, which is quickly becoming one of the leading universities in the chemical industry.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Front of it set the goal of training for high-tech industries of chemical technology.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In MITHT the first time in the country began to train engineers on the technology of thin inorganic products, synthetic rubber, thin organic produce synthetic liquid fuels, organometallic compounds and a number of other specialties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Special departments were prepared engineers for industries which were still being created in the first five years.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] At the time, were of great importance establishment of a domestic pharmaceutical industry and the country's liberation on imports of medicines.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Were developed and implemented methods of production of such drugs as atophan, benzocaine, procaine, bromural, thiokol, ichtyol, validol, antipyrine, caffeine, alkaloids and others.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In 1938, in MITHT under the leadership of academic A.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Nesmeyanov (later President of the RAS) began work in the field of organometallic compounds.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Also, the Institute prepared professionals for the companies producing such important national defense materials, such as tungsten, molybdenum, vanadium, and rare-earth elements.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Bashilov created the production technology of uranium and radium.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Meyerson were carried out important work on carbothermy and getting super-hard alloys.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] 7 May 1940 for academic achievement and great progress in the preparation of chemists institute is named after the outstanding Russian scientist Mikhail Vasilievich Lomonosov.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] During the war, groups of departments in collaboration with industry and research institutes conduct intensive research on defense-related development and implementation of the executed work.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Thus, under the supervision of Professor N.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Gelperin was created the most powerful bomb in World War II – FAB-5000NG that terrified Hitlerites.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Efforts of the Institute as a whole and individual professors and teachers were appreciated by the country.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Sirkin were awarded the Stalin Prize laureates, and associate professor K.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The post-war period was characterized by intensive work of the Institute staff in the aftermath of the war, the creation of the necessary conditions for teaching and research.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The high scientific – technical research conducted at the institute, evidenced by the fact that MITHT became one of the first places among the universities and research institutes on the number of implemented inventions.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Employees of the institute published 450–500 scientific papers and received 50–60 invention certificates a year.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] The institute conducts research on economic agreements and contracts on cooperation with industry and research institutes, whose number exceeded 150.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] MITHT, in fact, has turned into a complex of the university and research institutes.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] On 2500–3000 students, in addition to 400 professors and lecturers, employed more than 900 scientists.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Two to one – that is the ratio of students, academic and teaching staff, which was reached in MITHT.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Good specialist, engineer cannot be prepared without bringing him to participate in real, serious scientific research in the learning process.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] 11 February 1971 for his services to the training of specialists for the national economy and the development of scientific research institute was awarded the Order of the Red Banner of Labour.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Education in MITHT always featured a deep fundamental training, which included, along with a full range of natural sciences study the big cycle engineering and technological disciplines.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Special training was carried out by the so-called "thin" chemical technologies that are, as a rule, small capacity technology, implemented on the basis of the latest achievements of chemical science and technology.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] That is, in fact, the students received a university degree in combination with engineering training.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In 1992, the Moscow Institute of Fine Chemical Technology named after M.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Lomonosov has received a new, higher educational status – status of the academy.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] With the name change has changed the status and range of activities of the institute along with old technology, new specialty Humanitarian – Management Profile: "Economics and Management (chemical industry)", "Environmental Protection", "Standardization and Certification".
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] These specialties are subject to major technologies and solve their narrow-profile tasks.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Before the transition to a tiered structure the education of students was carried out in one direction, "Chemical Technology and Biotechnology", which consists of seven specialties.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] To implement in MITHT a tiered system of higher education were opened new training units.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Along with main faculties teaching of students was performed at the Faculty of Natural Science, Faculty of Humanities, Faculty of Management, Economics and Environment, Faculty of Engineering, Faculty of further education at the Institute of Distance Education.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] According to the Federal Agency for Supervision in Education and Science in 2008 in MITHT worked one of the most highly qualified scientific and technical teaching staff of universities and academies of Russia: doctors and candidates of sciences accounted for about 80% of the teachers.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] At the academy a total enrollment of 4,500 undergraduate and graduate students, taught 119 professors, doctors, and 218 associate professors, candidates of sciences.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] In 2011, the academy received a university status.
[src:moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies/moscow-state-university-of-fine-chemical-technologies] Friendly and supportive atmosphere of the business and human interaction with the students and teachers together form the necessary conditions for the development of the individual, focused, motivated professional growth.
